

TERA and Lyapunov Stability

1. TERA as a Stabilization System

In the TERA framework we define three conceptual spaces:

A(t) = perception space
B(t) = model space
C(t) = difference space = B(t) − A(t)

The goal of TERA is to keep the difference space small.

C(t) → minimal

or equivalently

|B(t) − A(t)| → stable

This is exactly the type of problem addressed in control theory.


---

2. Control Theory Formulation

A dynamic system is often written as

x'(t) = f(x(t), u(t))

where

x(t) = system state
u(t) = control input

For TERA we define

x(t) = C(t) = B(t) − A(t)

which gives

C'(t) = f(C(t), u(t))

TERA therefore acts as the logic that selects the control input u(t).


---

3. What TERA Does

TERA observes

C(t) = error / drift / difference

and applies a gate decision:

WAIT
ACCEPT
REJECT

This can be interpreted as a control rule

u(t) = Gate(C(t), I, E, ω)

which means

correction = function(error, information, energy, time)


---

4. The Lyapunov Idea

In stability theory we define a function

V(x) ≥ 0

that measures how far the system is from equilibrium.

For TERA a natural candidate is

V(t) = ||C(t)||²

which becomes

V(t) = ||B(t) − A(t)||²

This represents the energy of the difference between model and perception.


---

5. Stability Condition

A system is Lyapunov stable if

V'(t) ≤ 0

meaning

the difference does not increase

For TERA:

d/dt ||B(t) − A(t)||² ≤ 0

If this condition holds, perception space and model space remain coupled.


---

6. TERA Interpretation

TERA therefore attempts to

minimize drift over time

or more formally

stabilize C(t) = B(t) − A(t)

This is essentially Lyapunov-style stability logic.


---

7. Gate as a Controller

The TERA gate behaves like a discrete controller.

Example:

if ||C|| < ε1        → ACCEPT
if ε1 ≤ ||C|| ≤ ε2   → WAIT
if ||C|| > ε2        → REJECT

Mathematically this is a piecewise control function.


---

8. TERA Equation in Control Form

The TERA equation

ΔS = Gate(I · E · ω)

can be interpreted as

ΔS = u(t)

with

u(t) = Gate(I(t), E(t), ω(t))

The system update becomes

C(t+1) = C(t) + u(t)

or in general form

C(t+1) = F(C(t), u(t))


---

9. Relation to the Tetrahedral Structure

TERA uses four conceptual quantities:

A = perception
B = model
C = difference / planning
t = time

This gives

4 components

Geometrically this corresponds to a tetrahedral structure.

If TERA stabilizes these four quantities, it stabilizes the entire state space.


---

10. Importance of WAIT

The WAIT state is mathematically important.

Many controllers use a binary rule:

act / do not act

TERA introduces an intermediate state:

WAIT

This corresponds to

damped control
deferred actuation

in control theory.

It prevents unstable reactions under uncertainty.


---

11. TERA as a Feedback Loop

In control terminology TERA performs the following cycle:

observe error
estimate drift
apply bounded correction
re-evaluate stability

This forms a complete feedback control loop.


---

12. Minimal TERA Lyapunov Form

The minimal formulation is

C(t) = B(t) − A(t)
V(t) = ||C(t)||²

with the stability requirement

ΔV(t) = V(t+1) − V(t) ≤ 0

Interpretation:

ΔV(t) < 0  → convergence
ΔV(t) = 0  → stable equilibrium
ΔV(t) > 0  → instability

If instability occurs, the TERA gate decides

ACCEPT / WAIT / REJECT


---

13. TERA in One Sentence

TERA can be interpreted in control theory as

> a feedback system that regulates the difference between perception and model over time using discrete stability gates.




---

14. Minimal Equation

The minimal mathematical form of TERA is

C(t) = B(t) − A(t)
V(t) = ||C(t)||²

TERA rule:

choose u(t) such that ΔV(t) ≤ 0


